Fix bug in the mapping of raw symmetries in PwParser (#171)

The raw output of a PwCalculation contains fairly verbose information
about the symmetry operations found for the input structure. Since
storing these data structures as parsed from the XML output would be
very heavy on the database, instead these are mapped onto a static
dictionary of rotation matrices. This incurs some minimal but acceptable
information loss.

The process of mapping the original symmetry operations onto the reduced
operations was implemented by comparing the string name of the operation
and using the corresponding index to obtain the correct rotation matrix.
However, since the string comparison did not use an exact match as the
mathcing criterion, and in addition no break was used after finding a
match, the inverse symmetry operation always ended up getting matched.

To solve this, we change the string comparison to be an exact match, and
we break out of the loop when a match is found, for good measure.

A parser test is added to test for the correct mapping of symmetries.

Renamed and moved BaseWorkChain to BaseRestartWorkChain

This particular base workchain implements the notion of 'restarting'
a calculation from a previous calculation that did not complete
successfully until it does or a maximum number of iterations is
exceeded. This concept appears often, for example in QE pw.x
calculations that can restart if convergence was not reached.

Fix bug in parser_opts of PwParser and pass to parse_pw_text_output

The PwParser tried to retrieve the 'parser_options' from the settings
input node, but failed to convert the key to uppercase. Since during
calculation submission preparation all keys in the dictionaries are
converted to uppercase to ensure homogeneity, during parsing the
key never seemed to be specified. Converting the key to uppercase
now properly finds the parser options if specified.

The parser options are now also passed to the parse_pw_text_output
function.

Remove `prospector` and run `yapf` and `pylint` from repo (#526)

The `prospector` tools has been giving a lot of problems with dependency
incompatibilities since we have been using it and we really only use it
to run `pylint`. However, this is easy to run directly as well from a
remote, specifying the desired revision.

We do the same for `yapf` and remove the explicit dependency from the
`pre-commit` extra since the latter was not pinning a particular version
which could cause arbitrary style changes in different environments that
just happen to have a slightly different version.

Note that, although we also install `pylint` directly from a revision
in the pre-commit hook, we still have to define an explicit version in
the `extras_require`. This is because `pylint` needs to be run with the
`system` language defined in the hook, or it won't find all third party
dependencies that are installed and throw a lot of false positives about
missing imports. We define `~=2.5.0` which allows different patch
versions, which should not introduce incompatible linting.
